Most interpretations of technological determinism share two general ideas: the first one is that technological development itself follows a path that goes beyond the cultural or political influence; the second one is the idea that technology, in turn, has "effects in the societies that are inherent, rather than socialized.
For example, one might say that the automobile necessarily results in the development of roads.
However, a national road network is not economically viable for just a few cars, so new production methods are being developed to reduce the cost of owning a car.
